        "\n",
        "- The AI Premium: AI-related roles offer a clear, measurable premium across almost all U.S. states compared to non-AI positions. While the premium varies, the percentage increase peaks significantly in non-traditional tech states (like South Dakota and New Mexico) where employers must pay national market rates to attract scarce talent against lower local salary baselines.\n",
        "- Work Arrangement Flexibility: Fully remote roles command the highest Q1, median, and Q3 values, indicating that borderless national hiring pools for advanced tech talent drive remote compensation upward. Hybrid and on-site positions show highly similar median distributions, but hybrid roles exhibit a much broader spread due to its widespread adoption across vastly different corporate ranks and regional cost structures. \n",
        "- Industry Wage Volatility: Project-based, commission-heavy, and contract-driven sectors like Travel Agencies and Record Production & Distribution exhibit massive month-over-month wage volatility rather than flat baseline salaries. In contrast, more standardized, asset-heavy fields like manufacturing maintain entirely flat, predictable monthly salary trends.\n",
